But if we remember that he was all his life in the company of the foremost men of his time, we shall the less hesitate to attribute much of his learning to the opportunities thus given to him. The store he sets by official tradition accounts at once for his knowledge and his misconceptions. Altogether he may be summed up as a man of affairs, liberally educated and knowing enough to do his work intelligently. He is in no sense a learned man.
